ProjectsArray.Title: Project 1: Using Different Machine Learning Models to Predict Whether a Hotel Booking Will be Canceled or Not
ProjectsArray.About: After experimenting with different ML models, a model called RandomForest gets this job done accurately. It fits a decision tree classifiers on various sub-samples of the Hotel Booking dataset, and then averaging to improve its predictive accuracy and control over-fitting. Since the dataset is huge, roughly 69k samples, this model is accurate because it constructs multiple decision trees at the same training time. Lastly, it handles non-linearly data well. As a result, the model got an accuracy of roughly 88% to predict whether a hotel booking will be canceled or not!

ProjectsArray.Title: Project 2: Recommender System using C++.
ProjectsArray.About: It can recommend up to 100k movies based on its user and movie databases. I used unordered hash map, vectors and an algorithm called Tree Multimap to sort the movie and users from its respective databases and gather recommendations from them based on a certain criteria. So the complexities can range from different kinds of directors, genres, actors, e.g O(Log(D)) to O(log(A))

ProjectsArray.Title: Project 3: EXT2 Filesystem in C
ProjectsArray.About: Implemented a EXT2 Filesystem in C so that the kernal could mount it. This is a 1 MiB EXT2 FS with 1000 sized blocks and has a space for 128 inodes. It has 4 inodes: the root directory, lost+found directory, 1 regular file called hello+world, and 1 symbolic link that points to hello+world called hello. To test the FileSystem, make a directory called mnt. Then do sudo mount -o loop cs111-base.img mnt to mount your EXT2 filesystem. It should look like the following image:

ProjectsArray.Title: Project 4: Round Robin in C Simulation
ProjectsArray.About: This project uses a Round Robin algorithm in C Language, given the quantum length, process, PIDs, arrival and burst times. Also, this algorithm is based upon on a doubly linked list. It's already assumed that a single timed unit is the smallest atomic unit (cannot split it even longer).
